# The extralife loop

We rewrite open-source emulators to Rust → WASM and hang them off one React
component, so users can swap cores. **One core per build session.** Slow but
safe. Tests are the definition of done — grind until green, don't ship on vibes.

## The seam is sacred

Every core implements `extralife_core::Device` and *nothing about the React side
knows which console it is*. Do not add per-device methods to the component or the
JS API. If a device needs something new, it goes through the `Device` trait so
every core shares it. Change the trait deliberately and rarely.

## Order of work within a core's session

1. **CPU first, headless.** Port/implement the CPU and pass its SingleStepTests
   (per-instruction JSON with bus activity) before any video exists. Red/green
   before pixels.
2. **System level.** Wire PPU/APU/timers. Run community test ROMs headless.
3. **Golden pixels.** Diff the framebuffer against committed golden PNGs
   (dmg-acid2, cgb-acid2, etc.). That diff is done-ness.
4. **WASM + wire-up.** `wasm-bindgen`/`wasm-pack` build, lazy-loaded module,
   exposed through `<ExtraLife device="…" />`.

## Definition of done

- All applicable CPU tests pass.
- All targeted system test ROMs pass headless in CI.
- Golden-image pixel diffs are clean.
- `cargo test` green; the WASM module builds; the core loads via the component.

Non-trivial logic leaves one runnable check behind. Understand the hardware
before you write the loop — a small diff in the wrong place is a second bug.
